<Author>working_dadPI
<Content>Harassed by Security Personnel My family decided to take a long overdue vacation in Hong Kong. We decided to take the trip on the week inbetween Christmas and New Year of 2007 as it is the only days where we could share time together as a family. It was a 5 day trip where all accomodation and tours were booked ahead by our travel agent. On our second day, our first full day in Hong Kong, the itenerary was for a city tour. We were scheduled to be picked up by our guide at 8:30 in the morning. We we all excited and was at the Ramada waiting lounge around 7:30 AM, an hour earlier than the expected pick up time. While all 5 of us were there sitting and waiting, my son fell asleep. The security personnel gave us a not so friendly stare. That personnel paced around us several times with the same stare. After pacing around us for several times, he approached us and spoke in broken english, saying dont sleep. Sensing he could not speak fluent english, I let it go and said OK. A few more minutes passed and the stares were still there. Worst this time the stares were accompanied by head shaking. It is the type of a stare done by high school bullies. The constant stare were as if we had committed a serious crime that we had to be watched over very carefully. I complained to the manager about this harassment. I was told in no uncertain manner that it was their policy not to allow sleeping in the waiting lounge. That it was their board of directors who created the rule. I explained that we were waiting for our guide and falling asleep durig these times are normal. I also asked what was the rationale for this policy. Instead of explaining, the manager informed me that they could get fired if they wont wake people up. I then said that higher management should be advised that PAYING guests should be allowed to fall asleep without being disturb while waiting for their pick up. The manager responded that all hotels are like that. On the contrary, per our schedule, we transferred to Disney's Hollywood Hotel in Hong Kong for the Disneyland trip on our last day. In Hollywood Hotel I saw several people, in several occassions, dozing off while waiting for their bus rides or their guides. I made it a point to take note if any of the Hollywood staff would wake their guests up. The alleged claim by the Ramada manager that all hotels wont allow sleeping in waiting lounges NEVER happened in Hollywood. Harassment is not a great way to treat customers. I dont think there will be a next time for us in Ramada. I will also call my travel agent and inform them of this not so memorable experience. 
